These philosophers have a great infiuence in times of peace, as well as in times of war. Friend and foe submit to the song of the bard. Osten when two armies meet, and swords are drawn, and lances set, the bards throw themselves between the contending parties, and pacify them, as one by magio subdues the wild beast. And thus, even among the most savage non-Greeks, frenzy yields to wisdom, and Mars respects the Muses.2
